{{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|zoom=10|marker=religious-shinto|frame-align=center|frame-width=200|frame-height=250}}
}}'''Oyama Shrine'' (Oyama Jinja) is a {{ill|lt=Shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Shimane Prefecture|Q132751|WD=Q132751|1=Shimane Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Oki District|Q735735|WD=Q735735|1=Oki District, Shimane}}{{ill|lt=Nishinoshima Town|Q543193|WD=Q543193|1=Nishinoshima, Shimane}}. {{ill|UNKNOWN|WD=Q134917286|lt=Shikiuchi-sha|1=Shikinaisha}} is located at the north foot of {{ill|lt=Yakizan|Q11567667|WD=Q11567667|1=Mount Takuhi}}, the highest peak of {{ill|lt=Dozen|Dozen|WD=Dozen|ltq=Q11476216}}, to the east of Otsu village. It had a close relationship with {{ill|lt=Yakehi Shrine|Q11567668|WD=Q11567668|1=Takuhi Shrine}}, which was widely worshiped as {{ill|lt=guardian deity|Q131278957|WD=Q131278957|1=Guardian deities}} and was enshrined on the slope of Yakevolcano.

=== Enshrined God ===
*{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Mikoto Oyama|1=UNKNOWN}}
Although I don't see any particular theories, it is said that the yakivolcano that was originally called ``Oyama'' was {{ill|lt=Shintai|Q327532|WD=Q327532|1=Shintai}} ({{ill|lt=Shintaiyama|Q1595289|WD=Q1595289|1=Sacred mountains}}), and that the mountain itself was worshiped {{sfn|Edited by Shikinaisha Research Group|1983}}. This god and {{ill|lt=Usukega no Mikoto Shrine|Q11449116|WD=Q11449116|lt=Usukega no Mikoto|1=Ujika Shrine}} visit {{ill|lt=Hinamajhime no Mikoto Shrine|Q133940165|WD=Q133940165|lt=Hinamajhime no Mikoto|1=Hinamajihimemikoto Shrine}} There is a tradition that Uukega no Mikoto won due to the interference of {{ill|lt=Amanejaki|Q2417460|WD=Q2417460|1=Amanojaku}}.{{sfn|Nagami|1968|p=628}} After that, {{ill|lt=Yakikazan|Q11567667|WD=Q11567667|1=Mount Takuhi}} and {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Iekatsuyama|1=UNKNOWN}} (Atodo-san) competed again over {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Sakaki|1=UNKNOWN}}, and this time it was Heaven. It is said that the demons got in the way of Uukega no Mikoto, resulting in the victory of the god of Oyama, and as a result, sakaki trees flourished on Yakivolcano, but no sakaki trees grew on Mt. Ietaka {{sfn|Nagami|1968|p=628}}. It is said that the two gods are not on good terms because of this kind of relationship.{{sfn|Nagami|1968|p=628}}.

=== History == =The date of its creation is unknown, but as mentioned above, it is believed that it was originally established as a shrine to enshrine Daisen (a volcanic volcano) as a sacred mountain. Furthermore, 200 meters west of the enshrinement site is the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Hyogo Ruins|1=UNKNOWN}}, which appears to be a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=ritual ruins|1=UNKNOWN}} from the middle to late {{ill|lt=Kofun period|Q459939|WD=Q459939|1=Kofun period}}, and it is assumed that water or spring rituals related to agriculture were held there, but its relationship with this shrine is unknown {{sfn|Heibonsha edition|1995}}.It was known in the central government from an early period, and is listed in "{{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}" as a small shrine in {{ill|lt=Oki Province|Q1063829|WD=Q1063829|1=Oki Province}}{{ill|lt=Chibu District|Q11584565|WD=Q11584565|1=Chibu district}}. It is not known that the award of |Junior Third Rank |Q11591025}} is known, but in the ``{{ill|lt=Domestic Shinto Name Book|Q11420490|WD=Q11420490|lt=Inshu Shinto Name Book|1=Izumi Province Divine Name Register}}'' there is no rank called ``Junior Third Rank Upper<small>(Mama)</small>{{efn|Junior Third Rank Upper. }} Daisen Myojin” is written there. In the late {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}} (around the 11th - 12th century), when {{ill|lt=Sea of Japan|Q27092|WD=Q27092|1=Sea of Japan}} water transport in the {{ill|lt=San'in region|Q398310|WD=Q398310|1=San'in region}} began to develop in earnest, (Japan)||Kami}} came to be revered as the god of safe navigation, and Unjoji Temple (formerly known as Yakehi Shrine) was founded by a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=ascetic monk|1=UNKNOWN}} as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=sacred place|1=UNKNOWN}} for {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=mountain training|1=UNKNOWN}}. {{sfn|Heibonsha Edition|1995}}, and that {{ill|lt=Bettoto|Q2900274|WD=Q2900274|1=Bettō}} came to serve as the shrine's {{ill|lt=Negi|UNKNOWN|lt=Negishiki}} {{sfn|Shikiuchisha Research Group|1983}}. <small>(→See also "{{ill|lt=Yakehi Shrine|Q11567668|WD=Q11567668|1=Takuhi Shrine}}".)</small>In the Middle Ages, it seems that the {{ill|lt=Izumo Genji|Q11395897|WD=Q11395897|lt=Sasaki clan|1=Sasaki clan}}, the {{ill|lt=Izumo Genji|Q11395897|WD=Q11395897|lt=Sasaki clan|1=Sasaki clan}}, who aimed for stable control of Oki Province, tried to take control of this shrine, and {{ill|lt=Kenji|Q1327993|WD=Q1327993|1=Kenji (era)}}On September 5, 2016 ({{ill|lt=1276|Q5530|WD=Q5530|1=1276}}{{ill|lt=October 13|Q2925|WD=Q2925|1=October 13}}), the governor of Oki Province, {{ill|lt=Yasukiyo Sasaki|Q11382304|WD=Q11382304|1=Sasaki Yasukiyo}}, During the Negi era, he issued a letter to Jiren, a monk whose position was in crisis due to a conflict with the shogun, and relieved the Negi position and incorporated it into the ruling party. nk|Bottom|Q11360924}}'' (Kasagi family documents)</ref>{{efn|Jiren's ancestral office (Oyamasha Negi) and Kanda (Mitasho), which had been confiscated because he had violated the peasants, were returned to Jiren as a gift. }}{{sfn|Inoue|1982}}.

{{Quotation|Bottom ({{ill|lt=Yasukiyo Sasaki|Q11382304|WD=Q11382304|1=Sasaki Yasukiyo}} Kao<ref name="kamakuraibun16-12466" />)<br />{{ill|lt=Oki Province|Q1063829|WD=Q1063829|lt=Oki Province|1=Oki Province}} ({{ill|lt=Chibu District|Q11584565|WD=Q11584565|1=Chibu district}}) Mitashō Oyamasha Negi Jobji. <br />　　　　　　Monk Jiren<br />
